{{more footnotes|date=November 2015}}
The '''frog pond effect''' is the [[theory]] that individuals evaluate themselves as worse when in a group of higher performing individuals.

The frog pond effect is a part of the wider [[social comparison theory]].  It relates to how [[Self-evaluation motives|individuals evaluate themselves]] based on comparisons to other people around them, and is generally due to upward comparisons. Davis<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davis|first1=James|title=The Campus as a Frog Pond: An Application of the Theory of Relative Deprivation to Career Decisions of College Men|year=1966|url=http://www.utexas.edu/law/journals/tlr/sources/Volume%2092/Issue%206/Sander/Final%20Sourcelist%20Sourcepull/Sander.fn035.frogpond.pdf}}</ref> first noticed this effect when he discovered that students evaluated their performance as worse based on their peers from their school. MacFarland and Buehler<ref>{{cite web|year=1995|last1=MacFarland|first1=Cathy|last2=Beuhler|first2=Roger|url=http://psycnet.apa.org/journals/psp/68/6/1055.html|title=Collective Self-Esteem as a Moderator of the Frog-Pond Effect in Reactions to Performance Feedback}}</ref> theorized that the effect happens because individuals self-monitor within-group rather than compare across groups.  Individuals are affected by the frog pond effect the most when they come from an [[individualistic culture]], lack strong social connections, and have low collective [[self-esteem]].<ref>MacFarland and Beuhler, 1995</ref>

